I know that `JTable` can sort by a single column. But is it possible to allow for multiple column sort or do I need to write the code myself?
 sorter does not support multi-column sorting directly, but you can achieve this functionality by writing your own custom sorter.

Here's an example of how you might implement a custom sorter:

```java
public class MultiColumnSorter extends TableRowSorter<TableModel> {
    public MultiColumnSorter(TableModel model) {
        super(model);
    }

    @Override
    public void toggleSortOrder(int column) {
        int[] sortedColumns = getSortKeys().stream()
                .mapToInt(SortKey::getColumn)
                .toArray();

        if (Arrays.binarySearch(sortedColumns, column) < 0) {
            List<? super SortKey> list = Arrays.asList(getSortKeys());
            boolean ascending = true;

            // If all columns are already sorted in descending order, 
            // then we want to clear the sort keys.
            if (sortedColumns.length > 1 && sortedColumns[sortedColumns.length - 1] == column) {
                ascending = false;
            }

            list.add(new SortKey(column, ascending));
            setSortKeys(list.stream().toArray(SortKey[]::new));
        } else {
            removeSortKey(column);
        }
    }
}
```

You can use this custom sorter like so:

```java
JTable table = new JTable(model);
MultiColumnSorter sorter = new MultiColumnSorter(table.getModel());
table.setRowSorter(sorter);
```

Now, when you click on a column header, the table will first sort by that column in ascending order. If you click on the same column header again, the table will sort by that column in descending order. If you click on another column header, the table will sort by that column and keep the previous sorting intact.

