Develop a C++ algorithm to calculate the Fibonacci sequence, ascertaining the correct mathematical series starting from zero and one. Your algorithm should also support obtaining Fibonacci series with a different base, that is, instead of 0 and 1 the starting numbers could be any two integers provided by the user. 

Additional requirements: Handle boundary condition cases where the sequence might overflow and implement a mechanism to allow calculation of very large Fibonacci numbers efficiently. Explain the time complexity of your solution.
 Iterative Solution:

```C++
#include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

// Function to get nth Fibonacci number 
long long fib(int n) 
{ 
    if (n <= 1) 
        return n; 

    long long prev = 0, curr = 1, next; 

    for (int i=2; i<=n; i++) 
    { 
        next = prev + curr; 
        prev = curr; 
        curr = next; 
    } 

    return curr; 
} 

// Function to get nth Fibonacci number with custom start values
long long fib_custom(int n, int start1, int start2) 
{ 
    if (n <= 1) 
        return start1 + n * (start2 - start1); 

    long long prev = start1, curr = start2, next; 

    for (int i=2; i<=n; i++) 
    { 
        next = prev + curr; 
        prev = curr; 
        curr = next; 
    } 

    return curr; 
}

int main() {
    int n;
    cout << "Enter position in Fibonacci Series: ";
    cin >> n;

    // Default fibonacci series
    cout << "Fibonacci Number at position " << n << ": " << fib(n) << endl;

    int start1, start2;
    cout << "Enter first value of custom Fibonacci Series: ";
    cin >> start1;
    cout << "Enter second value of custom Fibonacci Series: ";
    cin >> start2;

    // Custom fibonacci series
    cout << "Custom Fibonacci Number at position " << n << ": " << fib_custom(n, start1, start2) << endl;

    return 0;
}
```

The above code uses an iterative approach to generate the Fibonacci sequence which is more efficient than the recursive approach.

Time Complexity: O(n)

This algorithm has a linear time complexity because it only requires a single loop that iterates n times. The space complexity is constant, i.e., O(1), since we are using a fixed amount of memory regardless of the size of the input.

Note: Be aware that this program may cause overflow for large inputs due to the limitation on integer sizes in most programming languages. For handling larger Fibonacci numbers, consider using arbitrary precision arithmetic libraries or data types that can handle large integers.

